If #Pharma decides to price gouge, they'll have to report manufacturing and R&D costs; net profits; marketing and advertising costs; patents and licensing; and executive compensation. This info will be critical for the HHS Secretary to utilize in negotiations to #LowerDrugCosts.

My comprehensive drug price transparency bill, the #FAIRDrugPricing Act (H.R. 2296), also passed through H.R. 3 today. This bill forces Big Pharma to publicly justify their price increases and will finally offer consumers greater transparency around drug pricing.

The @USCBO estimates negotiation would save the federal govt $456 billion--an INCREDIBLE sum that we'll use to finally offer vision, dental, & hearing coverage to seniors, as well as compression therapy through my #Lymphedema Treatment Act, which passed as a part of H.R. 3 today.

Negotiating for fair prescription drug prices is the most effective tool to #LowerDrugCosts and hold Big Pharma accountable for their price gouging. H.R. 3's lower, negotiated prices will be available to not just Medicare beneficiaries, but also people with commercial insurance.

We haven't been able to negotiate since Big #Pharma lobbyists, working with Congressional Republicans, added a prohibition on negotiation into law in 2003 in order to maximize their profits while patients suffered. I voted no then and have been fighting back ever since.

I was proud to vote for #LowerDrugCosts and hope President Trump will fulfill his promise to “negotiate like crazy” by pushing for H.R. 3 in the Senate and signing it into law. pic.twitter.com/HzIvmJ1Om2

Today the House passed H.R. 3, the Elijah E. Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act, and accomplished a transformative, historic step to #LowerDrugCosts for people across the United States. H.R. 3 will FINALLY allow the federal government to negotiate lower prescription drug prices.

The House’s work #ForThePeople never stops – especially at a time when over a quarter of American worry they may not be able to afford their prescriptions. We must pass H.R. 3 and #LowerDrugCosts as soon as possible! pic.twitter.com/q9auACI1Z9

This week, I’m joining my fellow @HouseDemocrats to pass the #LowerDrugCosts Now Act to make prescription drugs more affordable #ForThePeople!

Will @SenateMjrLeader let this important bill collect dust on his desk too?

68,560 of people in IL are diagnosed with cancer each year.

Most cancer medications cost patients an average of $100,000+ annually in the U.S. 

This week, I’m voting to #LowerDrugCosts, to help Americans afford lifesaving care.  #ForThePeople

For millions of women & their families, the cost of prescription drugs is not just a budget concern – it’s a health one. 

We need to #LowerDrugCosts so no Americans are forced to risk their health because prices are too high!

American families should not have to pay more for their medication than what people in other countries pay for the same drugs! 

This week, we’re voting to #LowerDrugCosts now, to give our families the help they need to afford their medication. #ForThePeople

In 2019, an estimated 11,560 of women will be diagnosed with breast cancer in IL.

On average, the total cost of the breast cancer medication Ibrance will cost those women $69,000 PER YEAR.

The #LowerDrugCosts act will lower that cost by 65%. Let’s make this a reality!
